deck_excerpt: Why is Mannadium GIGACHAD? Because Trif Gaming is a GIGACHAD, and all duelists who pilot his top 4 YCS list are GIGACHADS!
deck_description:
Post Age of Overlord, the main character of the current Yugioh saga Visas Starfrost gets a massive boost in terms of support! Now it's good to assume that Visas Starfrost has reached his FULL POWERLEVELS with AGOV, and now you can pilot the deck to unleash the power of the 4 emotions - FEAR, SADNESS, ANGER and PEACE!

 

Looking at the two new main support cards for Mannadium, Visas Samsara (additional extender and a normal summonable "Visas" name) and Trisukta (Enables 1 card combos/extension), Konami card designers intend to make Mannadium more resilient to interruption, less bricky and incredibly powerful. The Mannadium strategy of summoning a lot of negate-oriented boss monsters turn 1 and boardbreaking juggernauts turn2/3+ has been thoroughly streamlined and made much easier. 

 

Although not directly part of the archetype, Mannadium's relentless spam of material on the field enables it to summon I:P Masquerena for the incredible Extra Deck staple from AGOV S:P Little Knight - giving you two banish interruptions in one turn!

 

With all these cards from AGOV combined with support from previous recent sets, it seems that Mannadium is ready to break through to tier 1 status as this format's premier Synchro strategy! 

 

The decklist in this guide is heavily inspired by Trif's top 4 Indianapolis YCS finish with Mannadium - his version having a heavy emphasis on consistency (22 starters, with many of them being 1 to 2 card starters) and defensive play (12 defensive staples used). Be sure to check his video out!

 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
Post-AGOV, the structure of the MANNADIUM deck remains mostly the standard with only a few minor but impactful changes. In the maindeck, only 3 copies of Visas Samsara are added (Extender, starter, combo piece and additional "Visas Starfrost" name in field/GY). In the Extra Deck, 1 copy of Mannadium Trisukda has been included.
 
There are 9 NORMAL SUMMONS in this deck (8 monsters with the "heart" statline of 1500ATK/2100DEF along with 1 Reinforcement of the Army). There are 9 "PLANETS" in this deck (3 Calarium, 2 Reichphobia, 1 Perlereino, 1 Wraithsoth, 1 Terraforming). 3 Kashtira Fenrir fetch Scareclaw Kashtira from deck. Totalling 22 starters, these cards obtain missing combo pieces from deck, with many of them being 1 card starters. 22 starters out of 40 cards make this deck RIDICULOUSLY CONSISTENT! Any 1-2 card combinations of these cards are full combo + extenders, ending on the standard board and possibly more! 
 
12 DEFENSIVE CARDS are played - x3 Fenrir, x2 Triple Tactics Talent, x3 Triple Tactics Thrust, x3 Forbidden Droplet and 1 Infinite Impermanence. The ratio of these cards to the 40 card deck means that you'll typically draw 1-2+ of these and 3+ starters in the average opening hand - meaning that most hands are "playable." Coupled with Mannadium's inherent consistency + resilience to interruption, you'll win most of your games if piloted correctly (Unless you get Droll'd or Shifter'd)!
 
A small KASHTIRA package is included consisting of 3 Fenrir (Simultanously a starter + boardbreaker!) and Kashtira Scareclaw. Kashtira Scareclaw can be summoned from hand without normal summon to go into your Link-1 Light Heart so that you can fetch a combo piece - Reichheart or Visas Starfrost! 
 
The final layer of consistency is Trisukda. This extremely easy to summon card makes Visas Amritara, which in turn searches for your missing combo pieces.
 
S:P Little Knight with her bestie I:P Masquerena is included in the Extra deck to enable more interruption since they are very accessible in this deck with proper extenders. In situations where you have extra leftover material or have been floodgated to a standstill, I:P + another monster counts as two banishes!
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
There are several 1-2 card combos ending on basically the same board of 3-4 material Apollousa, level 10 Synchro bosses (Baronne, Dis Pater), and a set Mannadium Reframing (omni-negate that's sided in). All these negates generally stop your opponents dead on their tracks, leaving you to OTK next turn with your overwhelming board presence and follow-up. 
 
The strategy for Mannadium is straightforward (summon level 10 synchros + 3 mat Apollousa) and combos are linear, despite hands being different. In some cases where a combo step is interrupted, a skilled Mannadium pilot can pivot to another route and still end on a strong board! Any combination of cards generally leads to the same end board. Here is the main combo for Mannadium:
 
Riumheart + Mannadium Meek = Dis Pater (Negate monster OR Destroy monster) + Baronne De Fleur (omni-negate/destroy) + 3 Material Apollousa (3 monster negates) + if there are extenders you can summon S:P Little Knight + draw 1. Next turn, you'll have plenty of follow-up, especially 1-2 summons of Vicious Astraloud's coupled with it's monster pop. 
  1. Normal summon Riumheart to search for Abscission. 
  2. Special summon Meek. Activate Abscission targeting and destroying Meek, adding Calarium from deck. 
  3. Meek in GY activates. Special summon Meek from deck making it level 4.
  4. Activate Calarium to search for Visas Starfrost. 
  5. Banish Abscission in the GY to summon Visas Starfrost from hand. 
  6. Link away Visas Starfrost to summon Scareclaw Light-Heart. Search Reichphobia from deck. 
  7. Activate Reichphobia. Search Scareclaw Reichheart from deck (If you already have Reichheart search for Scareclaw Kashtira). 
  8. Special summon Reichheart from hand adjacent to Light-Heart. Search for Scareclaw Arrival from deck and draw 1 card. 
  9. Synchro summon Accel Synchro Stardust Dragon using Riumheart + Meek. Accel Synchro Stardust Dragon summons Meek again to the field from the GY. 
  10. Synchro summon Baronne using Accel Synchro Stardust Dragon + Meek. (Make sure you summon it in the middle, left of right zones so Cross-Sheep can point to it). 
  11. Link summon Cross-Sheep using Reichheart + Light-Heart so that Cross-Sheep is pointing to Baronne. 
  12. Special summon Vicious Astraloud using Riumheart + Visas Starfrost in the GY to a zone Cross-Sheep points to. 
  13. Cross-Sheep summons Meek from the GY. 
  14. Activate Baronne's effect to destroy Meek. 
  15. Meek in GY activates. Special summon Meek from deck making it level 4.
  16. Synchro summon Crimson Dragon using Vicious Astraloud + Meek. 
  17. Activate Crimson Dragon's effect targeting Baronne to Synchro summon Bystial Dis Pater. 
  18. Bystial Dispater summons from banished pile Visas Starfrost. 
  19. Special summon Light-Heart from GY. 
  20. Link summon Apollousa using Cross-sheep + Visas Starfrost + Light-Heart. 
  21. If you have any extenders, summon them to make either I:P Masquerena or S:P Little Knight. Set any spell/trap cards.
Every Mannadium hand generally leads to variations of this combo, resulting in the standard board of Baronne, Dis Pater, Apollousa and if you have extenders, S:P Little Knight. Left unchecked, this Mannadium's bread and butter combo ends on 1 omni-negate, 4 monster negates, 1-2 banishes, and draw 1. You also have materials in GY next turn to create a Astraloud and if Dis Pater survives until next turn, he can summon Riumheart from banished pile to as follow-up to get more resources from deck. In games 2-3 if you go first, Mannadium Reframing can get sided in so that the board will be protected against Dark Ruler No More or Droplet. 
 
The optimal deck's endboard is an extremely potent powerhouse that all decks would be hard-pressed to deal with. Depending on the cards in-hand and whatever interruptions your opponent has, your resulting endboard from this combo vary in power, depending on how much extenders you have and how many times you've been interrupted. 
 
This deck can also sustain being hit by several handtraps and keep on comboing, since it offers many extenders and different lines of play. Oftentimes this Mannadium can pivot into another route of play to keep on comboing. For example, has your normal summon been impermed? You can destroy it with Visas Starfrost then link him away for Light-Heart to go down the Scareclaw portion of the combo. 
 
Going second, this deck naturally breaks boards with Primitive Planet Reichphobia, Astraloud, Baronne and Accesscode Talker removing cards. 11 defensive cards are played in the maindeck, which can turn into 19 when siding during games 2-3. 19 boardbreaking cards along with Mannadium's 22 starters means that boards will be broken and full combo can be achieved most of the time - bar cards like Droll or Shifter. The math in this deck's card ratios checks out (again, shoutout to Trif and Pak for figuring these out)!
 
Mannadium can easily churn out over 9000ATK on board with at least 4 removals requiring minimal investment. When you've baited out all their interruptions going for the regular combo, you can pivot your strategy for the Astraloud + Accesscode OTK. First Link two monsters for Cross-Sheep on board. Contact fuse Visas Starfrost + Visas Clone in GY for Astraloud (1 pop) to a zone Cross-Sheep is pointing to so you can summon another monster from the GY. Then you can link the rest of the monsters on the field for Accesscode Talker.
 
GENERAL TIPS
  • As you combo, be aware of the zones you're summoning in, or else you may stop your combo in it's tracks! For Light-Heart, keep the monster zone below it empty, so you can summon Reichheart below it. For Cross-Sheep, make sure to leave space for both a synchro and fusion monster to summon underneath it so you can get an ATK boost and a monster reborn. 
  • High impact handtraps like Dimension Shifter, Droll & Lockbird, Nibiru and Artifact Lancea all stop this deck in it's tracks and/or severely limit it's play. While it is possible to play through these cards if your starting hand is strong, your board will be weaker. An option to use for this is 3 Crossout Designator + 1 of each handtrap to stop them (perhaps in sidedeck). 
  • if you've been handtrapped to oblivion, or your opponent flipped D-Barrier calling "synchros," then the general play is to end on S:P Little Knight with the resources you have left. It's better than nothing, and in a simplified gamestate she can win games! 
  • Is your combo stopped by a pesky floodgate on the field? No problem! One of your combo pieces, Primal Planet Reichphobia, destroys 1 card on the field! All it needs are at least 3 monsters on the field in defense position, which is an easy feat for this deck. Also Astraloud can destroy your opponent's floodgate monster on the field given it's materials are in the GY.
  • There are many other going-first combos with specific cards. Also, there are other playstyles of Mannadium that are playable, like the dreaded Calamity Lock! Be sure to check those out! A good place to start is Yacine's combo tutorial videos. 
  • Going second, you won't synchro much, despite Mannadium popularly known as a Synchro deck. You'll mostly summon Vicious Astraloud and Accesscode Talker to blow up your opponents board and attack for game! Making a Baronne will be ideal since it helps insulate your plays from interruption while destroying a card on the field. 
  • Astraloud's effects aren't once per turn. If your GY is packed with the proper materials, you can keep blowing your opponent's monsters up! 
  • If you happen to face a Expurrely Noir on the field, you can threaten the battle phase vs. it if you have a Kashtira Scareclaw on the field. The card's effect isn't activated, allowing you to negate the card if you declare an attack! If they shuffle away Kashtira Scareclaw, the card is now vulnerable to removal if it goes below 5 XYZ materials. 
  • Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
Compared to it's previous incarnations which I felt were uninspired synchro combo negate piles, Mannadium now feels fleshed out, fun and rewarding to play! Sure, Mannadium plays "solitaire" for a couple minutes burning through half of their deck to build an unbreakable board with a gazillion negates/interruption. What differentiates Mannadium from similar Synchro combo strategies like Adamancipator, Virtual World and the (now defunct RIP) Superheavy Samurai is it's ridiculous consistency (thanks to Trisukda and latest support), ability to break boards as it combos (Vicious Astraloud) and it's capability to quickly pivot from Synchro -> Link. 
 
Again, shoutout, thanks and congrats to Trif my Locals hero for this YCS decklist! Be sure to check out his video explaining his cards (probably much better than my humble guide lol). 
 
Harness the full power of your ANXIETY, DEPRESSION, RAGE AND JOY with post-AGOV Mannadium to defeat all your opponents and be the ultimate Visas Starfrost!
 
GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: Virtual World / Swordsoul hybrid that I used to win a locals! The deck isn't terrible.
deck_description:
Card Choices:

Main Deck:

The deck uses mostly standard VW ratios, I cut a copy each of the level sixes to keep the deck consistent. Two copies of Nyannyan as it's an important resource in the VW engine.

Two copies of Mo Ye and Longyuan as they're better to draw than Taia. Taia at one because the best use for it is to search off Emergence as the deck's only one card combo. Additionally, two copies of Ecclesia because I like it. It's good for consistency and saves the deck a normal summon going second. I usually side it out round two if I'm going first for more disruption (Dimensional Barrier, Denko Sekka, etc.).

Ash is the only hand trap in the deck because both engines are very space-heavy. Ash is generically good against most matchups. I also opted to play Dark Ruler No More as a board breaker instead of more hand traps as they have a greater impact for the number you run, making them a more space-efficient choice. Halfway through locals I was considering taking it out for something else, then I went against Dragon Link, resolved it three times, and won 2-0. It won't be coming out for the time being.

Pot of Desires is too powerful to remove even though it never draws the cards I want.

I took out Havnis and Shaddol Beast into Winda from my previous lists because the cards were too bricky and it wasn't worth investing all your resources into.

Extra Deck:

Both Swordsoul Sovereigns are included, though now Baronne is affordable, I might see if i can swap out Qixing Longyuan for one. Chenying is great for getting over big monsters. They can be made with the Swordsoul token / Ecclesia + Lili or another Lvl 6, but in Qixing Longyuan's case, it has to be a wyrm.

An OTK is easily accessible with most competent VW hands (Chuche on field, name in hand), as well as your opponent having a monster on field, by making 24 stars of material to make Utopia Beyond and Final Sigma. Utopia reduces the attack of the opponents monsters to 0, and Final Sigma deals double battle damage to monsters totalling to 9000 damage. If you can't quite make Final Sigma, you can use 18 stars to make Beyond plus Charge Warrior to hit all of your opponents special summoned monsters for 2000 each, and 3000 directly, but it requires your opponent to have 3 attack pos. monsters on board to OTK as opposed to one.

Yazi can summon Jiji or Lili from deck, and Baxia can summon Jiji from the GY, which opens up VW combos.

Stardust Charge Warrior is rad.

Zeus is only ever a backup plan for when you don't quite OTK I included it over a consistency card like Coral Dragon or Crocodragon because it is a really good backup plan.

Side Deck:

Dimensional Barrier is pretty good against something like Branded, but I feel isn't the best card to side in now. Same goes for Book of Eclipse.

Cosmic Cyclones and Harpie's Feather Duster are included to hit backrow decks, and decks with important continuous spell / traps. I prefer Cyclones to Twin Twisters because you don't need to discard an extra card.

Gadarla outs Expurrely Noir.

I included Denko Sekka because I don't like Labrynth.
Ruin & Demise

deck_name: Runick Prediction Princess ft. Back Mutation
deck_excerpt: An updated Runick Prediction Princess list with Back Mutation from PHNI
deck_description:
Back Mutation is a new card debuting in PHNI which acts as a playback to Metamorphosis, having an effect that mirrors it. Back Mutation Tributes a Fusion or Synchro monster you control in order to Special Summon a monster with the same original Level from your Deck, returning it to the hand during the End Phase. Metamorphosis would Tribute a monster to Special Summon a Fusion Monster with the same Level as the Tributed monster. With cards like Ready Fusion, Instant Fusion, and all of the Runick Quick-Play Spells, it is extremely easy to get a Fusion Monster out onto the field of a wide number of Levels to choose from. Ready Fusion Summons a Level 6 or lower non-effect Fusion Monster, Instant Fusion Summon a Level 5 or lower Fusion Monster, and the Runick cards give you access to Sleipnir the Runic Mane as a Level 9, Freki the Runick Fangs as a Level 5, Geri the Runick Fangs as a Level 4, Munin the Runick Wings as a Level 3, and Hugin the Runick Wings as a Level 2. Sure, there are a variety of different monsters of different Levels to Summon off of Back Mutation, knowing what Fusion Monsters you can readily get out of the Extra Deck, but I am looking at Prediction Princess because Back Mutation is basically another way to get Prediction Princess Bibliomuse out of the Deck and into rotation. I've already made a Runick Prediction Princess list, but that was about half a year ago from the posting of this Deck. Now, I know more of what ratio of cards I should be playing, what Extra Deck cards I should focus on, and this new list utilizes the best of all of the new cards Prediction Princess can make use of. 

Main Deck monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotreith and 1 Prediction Princess Tarotrei. Tarotreith can be Ritual Summoned or Summoned from hand or GY via Tarotrei's End Phase effect. On Flip, it can Summon a Flip Monster from Deck face-down and as a Quick Effect, it can Flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Tarotrei can Quick Effect Flip a monster face-up or face-down and can Summon a Flip Monster from hand or Gy in face-down Defense Position duringthe End Phase. 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse which on Flip adds a Prediction Princess monster other than itself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand. If it's Tributed and sent to GY, it can Summon itself back face-down, and while on field, it gives your Ritual Monsters targeting and destruction protection. 2 Deus-X Krawler which negates all of your opponent's monsters' activated effects on field after it has been flipped face-up, and when it's destroyed on field, it can add a Level 9 with a different Type and Attribute than it from Deck to hand. 1 Pot of the Forbidden. We are playing this because there are situations where you will have Trias Hierarchia on field and a World Legacy Monstrosity in hand. If you are in a situation where you have access to no Runick cards for Sleipnir, you need a target in Deck to Summon in addition to Deus-X Krawler when targeting Hierarchia with Monstrosity. The best target in a Deck like this would be Pot of the Forbidden, a fellow Level 9 Flip Monster. On Flip, you can choose to Draw 2 cards, bounce all Spell/Traps on field to hand, Destroy all monsters your opponent controls, or look at your opponent's hand and shuffle a card from it back into the Deck. Usually I wouldn't play Pot of the Forbidden unless it is a situation like this where you need an extra target in Deck for Monstrosity, but while each of its effects belong to a banned card (aside from Raigeki), they aren't really that good after the DABL Prediction Princess Support. Draw 2 card? You are already searching a Prediction Princess monster (other than Bibliomuse) and a Ritual Spell from flipping up Bibliomuse. You have the cards you want to see in hand already. Why would you need extra draws for 2 random cards that may or may not help you as much compared to what Bibliomuse already searched you for your following turn? Bouncing all Spell/Traps on the field to the hand? Unless you know that you are up against a backrow Deck and are going first, you are usually going to be Summoning Deus-X off of Tarotreith and not Pot of the Forbidden. If you do know, then you would get Pot from Deck with Tarotreith and bounce your opponent's backrow during the End Phase, yes. But sometimes you don't know your specific match-up, so there is no real reason to shotgun Pot of the Forbidden. Destroy all monsters your opponent controls? Man, your opponent is barely going to be getting anything worthwhile onto the field when you have Deus-X flipped up. And if your opponent's Deck gets many monsters onto the field without needing on-field monster effect activations, then, how would you know the match-up in the first place? Forceful Sentrying your opponent? I'm not too sold on this either. There are some situations where yes, it would be good and useful, but at the same time, you aren't shotgunning Pot of the Forbidden off of Tarotreith. Deus-X has a much more powerful effect, and if you are aiming to get rid of your opponent's board breakers, sure, but half of them are already covered by Bibliomuse who gives your Ritual Monsters targeting and destruction protection. The only real threats are Dark Ruler, Evenly Matched, Kaijus, and Imperming a flipped up Deus-X, but you don't really need to worry about those things unless it's game 3 and you went first game 1. And to be fair, many people don't know the Prediction Princess match-up. And in this Deck specifically, we still have the Runick cards to fall back on. So that is a little lecture on why Pot of the Forbidden isn't as "good" or as needed in a post DABL Prediction Princess list. Moving on, 1 Trias Hierarchia and 3 Diviner of the Herald. Trias is another very easy-to-access Level 9 who can be sent off of Diviner, and can tribute a Fairy to Summon itself from hand or GY. This includes Hugin to clear up your Extra Monster Zone. Diviner sends a Fairy from Deck or Extra Deck to GY, increasing its Level by that of the sent monster's. You can send Hierarchia to put it in rotation, or you can send Herald of the Arc Light from Extra for a Ritual Search.

For Spell/Traps: 3 Back Mutation. Again, this Tributes a Fusion or Synchro to Summon a monster from Deck with the same original Level, returning it to the hand during the End Phase. We are playing 2 of the Runick Fusions in this Deck. Sleipnir the Runick Mane is a Level 9 that can be Tributed to get Prediction Princess Bibliomuse or even put Hierarchia into rotation. Hugin the Runick Wings is a Level 2 that can be Tributed to get Diviner of the Herald from Deck. Yes, you heard that right. It can readily get Diviner out of the Deck for either a Ritual Search or to send Hierarchia to put it into rotation. Very nice card. 2 World Legacy Monstrosity. It can Summon a Level 9 from hand or target a Level 9 on field and Summon 2 Level 9's with different names from Deck with a different Type and Attribute than the target. We are still playing this because it is still a very good card in Prediction Princess. Not only can it readily access the Aggregator line, it is basically a free Rank 9 in some situations. 1 Instant Fusion to get Master of Ham from the Extra Deck. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down. And you can banish it during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess from Deck face-down. 2 Runick Fountain which allows you to activate Runick Quick-Play Spells from hand during yoru opponent's turn. And if you activate a Runick Quick-Play Spell Card, you can target up to 3 Runick Quick-Play Spells in your GY, return them to the bottom of the Deck and draw the same number of cards. This is great for digging deeper into your Deck for Ritual pieces and Bibliomuse. Next up, 3 Runick Freezing Curses, 3 Runick Tip, 3 Runick Slumber, 3 Runick Flashing Fire, and 3 Runick Destruction. All of them can Special Summon a Runick Monster from the Extra Deck to your EMZ. Freezing Curses negates the effects of an effect monster your opponent controls until the End Phase, banishing 3 cards from the top of their Deck. Tip adds a Runick card from Deck to hand except itself, banishing the top card of your opponent's Deck. Slumber prevents the next destruction of a targeted face-up monster on the field this turn, banishing the top 3 cards of your opponent's Deck. Flashing Fire targets and destroys a Special Summoned monster your opponent controls, banishing the top 2 cards of their Deck. And Destruction targets and destroys a Spell/Trap your opponent controls, banishing the top 4 cards of their Deck. 

Extra Deck: 2 Sleipnir the Runick Mane and 2 Hugin the Runick Wings. I know that Sleipnir has an effect, but I don't care because we are never going to be using it in this Deck. It's just a Level 9 for Monstrosity and Back Mutation. Hugin can discard a card to add a Runick Field Spell from Deck to hand and she can banish herself from field to protect another card(s) you control from destruction, and she's also a Level 2 for Back Mutation. 1 Master of Ham. It Summons a Flip Monster from Deck face-down when its Fusion Summoned, which is going to be via Instant Fusion in this Deck. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which adds a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from Deck to hand when it's sent to GY. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 1 Infinitrack Earth Slicer which can detach any number of materials to pop the same number of cards on field, and if it destroys a monster by battle, it can attach it to itself which makes it good for boardclearing and making Zeus. 1 Mereologic Aggregator which can send a monster from Extra Deck to GY on Xyz Summon, and it can target monsters in your GY and detach an equal number of Xyz Materials to attach those monsters to itself which can be used to loop a Herald of the Arc Light you sent off of Xyz Summoning said Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity for Rank 9 and interruption options. 1 S:P Little Knight. 1 I:P Masquerena, and 1 Gravity Controller.

Side Deck: 3 Lava Golem we don't necessarily need our Normal Summon in this Deck, so having a way to clear multiple threats on your opponent's field without activating a card effect is pretty good. 3 Kashtira Fenrir. 2 Triple Tactics Thrust. 1 Herald of the Abyss. 2 Evenly Matched. 1 Dimensional Barrier, and 3 Solemn Judgment.

deck_excerpt: Salamangreat deck with a small FTK engine
deck_description:
i'll skip over the regular salamangreat plays because the deck can play like any regular salamangreat deck post promethean princess

instead i'll focus on explaining the FTK, it's not very complicated

the 2 cards you must fetch are salamangreat weasel and salamangreat sanctuary, besides that all you need is a way to summon salamangreat raging phoenix WITHOUT promethean princess and by using heatleo (IMPORTANT) to climb into it

let's go with a combo example, i used a random test hand because there's a ton of ways to do the combo so focusing in just one is pointless

the first thing you want to do is get the field spell with balelynx:

then, get 4 materials worth of link mat and at least 1 more summon, also have weasel in field or GY (or hand as the extra summon)

you must climb into raging phoenix using heatleo (in theory any link-3 fire that can be summoned from gy later works)

once you summon raging phoenix, summon it again by using its copy as mat to search will of the salamangreat and use its second effect 

use 3 of the summoned monsters to link summon promethean princess, then use her effect to summon heatleo, you need to have weasel on the gy or field ready to be used as material for the next step and an extra level 4 or lower FIRE monster in the field

after this, summon salamangreat pyro phoenix by using either link-3 and raging phoenix (it's important to keep a level 4 or lower FIRE monster), then use weasel's effect to summon a raging phoenix to your opponent's side of the field and use pyro phoenix's effect to burn your opponent for -2800

here, use the extra summon and pyro phoenix to summon "hiita the fire charmer, ablaze", your field should have 1 level 4 or lower FIRE monster, hiita and one link-3 monster at this point

then from your deck (or hand) summon greater inari fire by tributing the level 4 or lower FIRE monster and hiita, use its on-summon effect to burn 2800 more LP (after that your opponent would be at 2400 LP)

then, link away greater inari fire and your link-3 to summon any link-4 with 2400+ original atk (for example, amblowhale), and use greater inari's second effect when sent to GY to search spiritual fire art - kurenai

set kurenai, pass turn and in the draw phase simply use kurenai by tributing your link-4, dealing the finishing blow to your opponent

 

and that's the FTK (technically it's not an FTK since it ends at the start of your opponent's turn, but there's not much your opponent can react with to win this situation)

only warning i'd give is, if you know your opponent is playing purrely skip the FTK as pretty memory will save their ass, also this FTK is very weak to interruption but as per usual with FTKs it's immune to blowouts, if you suspect your opponent could handtrap you i'd recommend simply skipping the FTK and going for a safer salamangreat board

the deck, in general, is also fine as a regular salamangreat deck since the FTK is very low-commitment in main deck and extra deck space (without counting cards that you'd regularly run in salamangreat, it's 2 main deck cards and 1 extra deck monster)

i recommend trying out test hands before giving it serious plays, so you can get a feel of various play lines needed to reach the FTK

have fun jumpscaring people with a surprise FTK if you try this

 

pointless note: i generally don't post my decks anywhere, but in this case this is a theorycraft that i've never seen anyone come up with (as far as i know, i could very easily be wrong and look like a tool), so i'm making this as an archive of "i made this first" proof, also i went 4-0 in a pre-realese test tournament with this and the FTK worked out quite a few times and the regular salamangreat pivot also worked so i feel confident enough in the fact that it's not 100% a meme
Burn them fast or burn out! Edit: Play this in the Edison Format. At the time of uploading, Ygopro's deck builder does not allow Nurse Reficule in the Edison Format.

deck_excerpt: What are pyramids made of? Bricks.
deck_description:
Triamid is that one deck i desperately tries to make work for some time now.

After playing some N/R format with some friend, i finally decided to take the plunge and make a proper Triamid deck. It sucks. Probably.

N/R Triamid was the most fun in dueling i ever had, regular ranked duels with it are... not so much. You'll spend the majority of the time hoping your opponent doesnt do any of the usual solitaire you normally see.
===============================================================================================================

So what's the game plan? It's pretty simple, really :

 

I dont think its a good idea to have someone who's actually bad at the game to explain a deck, but do allow me to explain the pawns that you will be using.

Triamid Sphinx : You might think he's the boss monster here, the big daddy of the deck, but no (for the boss mon part, yes for the big daddy part). You can remove him from the deck and it wont change much, heck it might make the deck more useable. No, he is a symbol for the deck, and summoning him is basically you making a statement towards your opponent "I am taking your carefully built deck with Triamid, prostate yourself in awe". He is a big monster that can beat your enemy down, but doesn't do much other than having a pressence. Just like a pyramid.

Triamid Hunter : The core, the main dish of the deck. The extra normal summon that makes the deck have some field pressence. Pretty straightfoward card, useless without the field spell.

Triamid Dancer : The salad dressing, sauce and the one that give this deck a fighting chance. The name of the game is "Your LP drops to 0 3 turns from now" and she will make sure it happens. In a long game, which you should alway aim, she will keep powering up your bricky mons, turning everyone into a beatstick.

Triamid Master : He exist.

Fossil Dyna Pachycephalo : Do i really need to explain about him? Summoning two is the dealbreaker, your enemy wont get through, and we are more than well equipped to do just that.

Neo-Spacian Grand Mole : An unexpected best friend of the deck! Remover of annoying monster, and its not like you can summon him just once you know.

Adamancipator Researcher : She's great because you only need a rock monster to special summon her, and she special summons another on excavate, heck you really should just go full Adamancipator instead of Triamid :/

Triamid Cruiser : Your normal summon best field, heals and draw on triamid summon, also search one when replaced. Set it up first and set it up last.

Triamid Fortress : Remember to have this on field when you active Torrential Tribute, because that's the only mass removal you got. Your Triamid is layered with anti-Raigeki with this pile of brick on the field.

Triamid Kingolem : When everything's set up neatly and in line, it's time to go the offensive. Attack boost and protection on battle phase, also special summons from hand when replaced, but keep it as a surprise!

Adamancipator Friends : "Why even use this card? It locks into rock only!" That's the thing babe. It's a none otp excavate that increases with the number of rocks you got on your field. Aside from MaxxC, your deck is all rock, and we need all the chance to summon Dyna.

And what about the Extra Deck?

You can just ignore it. Besides, you're not going to use the Extra Deck anyway. You need the Triamids on field to keep swapping the field, Dyna doesn't allow special summons anyway and Researcher is there for excavate. The Extra Deck is there if you're that desperate, but we don't do that here.

===============================================================================================================

So how to use the deck?

Im no expert, but here's what you need to aim for :

1. A field and 1 Triamid. This is the bare minimum, and you will probably be dead next turn.

2. Rush in 2 Dyna as fast as you could, you can search them up with excavate.

3. Once you establish field pressence, continue to recycle with Triamid Dancer and you will be battering your enemy to death with those massive attacks.

4. There's also the surrender button.

Best Combo :

- Place Triamid Cruiser

-Normal Summon Triamid Hunter

-Special Summon Adamancipator Researcher

-Excavate - Special Summon Dyna

-Normal Summon Dyna

-Thats it.

It kinda sucks that we have to rely on floodgates at the end of the day, but we play with the card in our hand, and Triamids are some bad cards. Happy dueling.

deck_excerpt: Touched by an Angel: Unveiling the True Identity of Gabriel
deck_description:
Archangel Gabriel Profile:

Angel who has a talent for etiquette and refinement. His mission is to create harmonious connections and promote relationships between people, as well as balancing differences and adjusting contrasts. However, this angel has an exaggerated dose of vanity.Justice is an essential characteristic of this angel, who demonstrates remarkable tolerance, capacity for conciliation and collaboration. For Gabriel, love is the essence of life, making it colorful and tasty. He wants to explore the feeling to the fullest and is in no rush, preferring to carefully observe every movement of the loved one and imitate it.

His approach to his friends is unique, as he knows the expectations and weaknesses of each of them, always ready to offer words of encouragement in difficult times. Gabriel loves parties and doesn't refuse an invitation, he loves shopping and bargaining with people. When he was younger, he was always close to his siblings, enjoying fun times and sharing activities.

Gabriel values his appearance a lot and knows how to balance his commitments to avoid work overloads. When confronted emotionally, his tendency is to stall for time or ask for help, thus relieving the weight of responsibility. Living with people is very important to Gabriel, who feels despair at the thought of being alone for a short period of time. He needs company to feel comfortable.

In the family environment, Gabriel demonstrates his virtues in his judgments. He enjoys contact with other people and finds pleasure in his work, although he may occasionally be attacked by laziness or hesitation. His favorite color is pink and he prefers soft fragrances, with the delicate aroma of bouquets of roses or orchids. His biggest dream is to be surrounded by interesting and beautiful people, living in a luxurious environment and enjoying exquisite places. Gabriel simply loves chic!

Gabriel's main qualities include kindness, elegance, wisdom, pacifism and diplomacy. On the other hand, its disadvantages include hesitation, inconstancy, omission, laziness, vanity and the habit of taking or consuming unnecessarily. His biggest fear is going through scandals or embarrassment in front of people, which only increase his feeling of shame. Although he loves interacting with people, any confrontation or fight leaves him in a panic. The constant worry about making the right choice fuels your fears about the future and any threat to your stability is a cause for concern.

deck_excerpt: Colossus is a MISTAKE! Get it? Thunder Dragon is still a Masters 1 worthy strategy with Bystials!
deck_description:
This deck is an updated version of an earlier decklist I made from August 2023. Feel free to check the guide out!

With Bystial cards enabling banishment from the GY and the Thunder Dragon's effects triggering when getting banished, it seems like these two archetypes were made for each other! They support each other's weakpoints and enable each of their effects. Level 6 Bystials/Thunder Dragon + Assault Synchron also allow for the easy summon of Chaos Ruler in this deck, another valuable playstarter for this strategy, packing the GY, banishing lights/darks and providing a total of 3 level 8 bodies on board for Synchro or Link summons! Going first, this deck typically makes a 3-4 negate Apollousa, a search-floodgate with Colossus, multiple pops with Titan and the Bystial engine is set-up! Going second, this deck can plow through negates/interruption while having enough gas to clear the opposing board and OTK.

GLHF Duelists!

Placement: 1st Place

"Nothing will save you from humiliation!"-Seto Kaiba

You are now Seto Kiaba once you use this deck

Testing Valmonica Dream Miror

The deck is meant to be a fun/casual deck, mostly with cards that I like or that look cool.

 

The main line of the deck is:

Summon Neiroy the Traitor, add Neiroy the disciple, special summon the disciple then use traitor's effect to get Dream Mirror of Terror, sacrifices the disciple, get Ikelos Sprite, use effect for the fusion spell, then fusion summon Erlking or Tormentor.

You could also go the xyz way with the xyz armor package.

If you already have the fusion in your hand or the 3 resonnance counters, you can also get Morpheus White Knight, use effect to go into Morpheus Black Knight, and use the traitor for fusion summon with the graveyard or link summon Valmonica.

 

If you want to play the Valmonica's field, I would recommand playing only one copy and terraforming, because we need to get to the Dream Mirror's fields in the early game.


Any ideas on how to make the deck better is welcome !

Harpies are a classic Yu-Gi-Oh! archetype, and for good reason. They're fast, aggressive, and can put up some serious damage. This Harpie deck is no exception.

With a focus on swarming the field and using Harpies' powerful effects, this deck can quickly overwhelm your opponent. Harpie Harpist and Harpie Perfumer can search out your other Harpies, while Harpie Channeler and Harpie Lady 2 can special summon them from your hand. Harpie Queen and Harpie Lady Sisters are both powerful boss monsters, and Harpie Oracle can negate your opponent's monster effects.

In addition to the Harpie monsters, this deck also includes a number of powerful staples, such as Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit, and Effect Veiler. These cards can help you disrupt your opponent's plays and give you the time you need to set up your own.

The Extra Deck is packed with powerful monsters, including Cyber Slash Harpie Lady, Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder, and Mecha Phantom Beast Dracossack. These monsters can give you the edge you need to finish off your opponent.

*As of November 7th this deck is worth about 50$ (I try to go below) on TCGPlayer without tax or shipping. Prices also may vary.

I actually had some spare money from making the main deck and extra and every main or Extra Deck upgrade is a bit too expensive than what the budget allowed so I build a little small and cute Side Deck for this. The Baldrakes are for the mirror, book of eclipse for Purrely, and Heartbeat is for Labrynth or maybe Rescue-ACE. Anyways this deck actually has the potential to be about as strong as it's full power version. You're just missing some consistency, and Extra and Side Deck ultility. For potential upgrades I'd consider investing in more Tearlaments Kashtira first. It's a bit expensive but it really is a great card for this deck. It's great to open, it's great to mill, and it allows you to play through more. Past that I'd probably recommend focusing on the Extra or Side Deck after that. Guardian Chimera and Baronne (with Diviner) are great cards, but too pricy for a budget list like this. Tearlament is actually a very customizable deck so feel free to cut or add whatever you like to the Deck.

deck_description: U can play this to get used to Swordsoul:D

Just wanted to make a Volcanic deck after all these years, I loved them way back when and with the new support I'll be eager to play them again! I'm a bit unsure on what to do for the extra deck. I will maybe update this a bit further once more Fire Support comes out, but I am also considering trying Volcanic Snake Eyes I'm just not sure how to go about it, any help is appreciated!

Technically this is not a Tistina Deck at all because it abuse a lot of broken card rn to be viable. The Tistina archetype is not a weak archetype to begin with, they just lack of meaningful boss monster to go to. Their going 2nd power is incredible so i pair them up with some broken going 1st card like Ken and Gen with Triple Tactics to ensure we start with some advantage. 

This build can also abuse the Acid Golem lock easily because of their powerful recursion like Hound and Sentinel. The video should demonstrate it.

With the release of the DUNE support back in August, Urarctic is one of those decks that really can make a troublesome board and still have gas in the tank for more. With the help of Urarctic Radiation, which can be abused to allow them to draw 14 at most, and the new level 1 synchro that easily creates a boss monster that just stops your opponents EX deck monster effects. Crossout Designator is the main card that will help you avoid those troublesome handtraps that could put a end to your plays like Nibiru and Droll. Main goal of the deck is to keep special summoning Ursarctic monsters so you can continue to get a draw off of Radiation, so you can fill your hand back with cards you can use to summon. if you run out of tokens on Radiation, use Baronne's pop effect and activate a new one and then continue with combo's.

deck_excerpt: Branded Despia  / UK Open Manchester 2023 Top 8
deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Luke Tyler

Tournament: UK Open Manchester 2023 – November 4th 2023 & Canterbury WCQ Regional Top 8 - October 7th 2023

Placement: Top 8
A deck of heroes to try
Arkana - Anime - Battle City

A while ago, Naturia Runick was pretty good. However, Sacred Tree got limited to 1, so it died. However, no one needs Runick. They're only a meta engine, how could can they be? Whatever. The deck used Naturia cards, Vernuslyph cards, and obviously Runick. When I made my previous Naturia deck, I had just gotten back to yu-gi-oh and did not know Vernuslyph existed. So I decided to remake it.

This deck mainly likes to go first. It has many different plays it can make, but most of them lead to Naturia Camellia on field with either Sunflower or Mole Cricket in the graveyard. Due to how simple this setup is, it is very resistant to interruption, has 3 summons maximum, and most importantly, very consistent. If you can, get out Vera with Camellia or Mole Cricket on field or in the graveyard.

If you manage to disrupt your opponent enough, on your turn you can start your synchro plays. While the deck has many copies of the Naturia synchros, its mainly so you can ladder with Cricket. This combo lets you easily access most level 10 synchros. You can go into Crystal Wing, Baronne de Fleur, or MAYBE Shenshen. If you can go for game, go into Draco Berserker of the Tenyi. Keep in mind, if you use a Vernuslyph monster, you can't use the effects of Crystal Wing, Baronne, Shenshen, or Draco Berserker. 

Alternatively, you might be able to get away with getting out Naturia Beast and Vera along with the Camellia & Sunflower combo.

So going second. This is tougher, but not impossible, especially games 2 & 3. But if its game one, make sure you draw into your handtraps. But in the event you don't, what do you do? This obviously varies depending on the board, but ideally you could summon Vera and take something. You try going into Draco Berserker and just beating over their board. Yeah this deck is not good going second.

But lets say you have the side deck. What can you do then? In the side deck you will find 15 going second cards. Make sure to put them in the deck. Now Landoise's Luminous Moss is not the best card, but its funny so its in the deck. If you're feeling funky you can also use it going first.

In case you have trouble, I'll detail the most common ways to get out your synchros.

Naturia Beast -> Naturia Camellia & Naturia Mole Cricket

Naturia Barkion -> Naturia Camellia & Naturia Sunflower 

Level 8 synchro -> Naturia Camellia & Naturia Mole Cricket make Naturia Beast, Naturia Mole Cricket revives itself & summons Naturia Rosewhip, Naturia Beast & Naturia Rosewhip go into the level 8

Virtual World Kyubi - Shenshen  -> Same as above, but Naturia Camellia instead of Naturia Rosewhip 

Level 10 -> Same as level 9, but Naturia Barkion instead of Naturia Beast (you'll need to have Naturia Mole Cricket in your graveyard beforehand)

Superheavy Samurai Brave Masurawo -> Naturia Camellia & a level 8, either a synchro or Vera

Please note that most of the extra deck is just random synchro monsters that this deck can go into. The only ones that I'd say are 100% nessecary are Naturia Beast, Naturia Barkion (can go down to 1 if nessecary), Crystal Wing, and Baronne de Fleur. You can swap out the others if you like. Add in Utopic Draco Future or something. Go crazy.

deck_name: A Beginner's Guide to Horus Bystial {November 2023)
deck_excerpt: YCS Indianapolis coolest decklist is "Horus Bystial!" Almost like Dragonlink without the long combos!
deck_description:
One of the most interesting topping decklists from the recent YCS Indianapolis is "Horus Bystial" piloted and invented by Kailyn "Cookie" Cooksey-Garcia! Here is the link to their YGOPRODECK deck profile and their Youtube video. 
 
It turns out that slapping together beatstick handtraps (Bystials), level 8 extenders (Horus) and a tuner package (Resonators) is enough to top a professional Yugioh tournament! 
 
Functioning as a midrange-aggro deck with a robust resource grindgame, Horus Bystial kind of reminds me of Dragonlink except with more Synchro boss monsters and less combo steps! Ever since this interesting strategy's inception, I wanted to give the deck a try because I have a soft spot for unique aggro decks with a "control then OTK" playstyle. 
 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
The standard HORUS package is included in this deck, their role primarily allowing access to rank 8 plays. 3 Imsety, 1 Hapi and 1 Duamutef comprise this package. The 4th Horus monster isn't included since it's largely a brick and has little utility other than being a beatstick (this deck already has a lot of them). 2 King's Sarcophagus is included rather than 3 since it is searchable with Imsety. 
 
A sizeable BYSTIAL core is in this deck, responsible for a large portion of control and to provide bodies to synchro and XYZ summon. 3 Lubellion and 3 Saronir are included to maximize consistency. 1 Magnamhut, 1 Druiswurm and 1 Baldrake are included for their utility. 1 Branded Regained and 1 Branded Beast are maindecked to provide more resources board presence and control. In the side deck, 1 Etude of the Branded is present since it's a searchable floodgate (Banish for all your opponent's monster summon materials) that can quick-synchro your monsters during your opponent's turn. Bystial Dis Pater in the Extra deck is very accessible in this deck, and can loop combo pieces by recycling them from banished to the field.
 
A small GENERIC DRAGON oackage is included, composed of 3 Black Metal Dragon, Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon, 1 Chaos Dragon Levianeer and 1 Chaos Space. Chaos Space can either search Lubellion or Levianeer depending on the attribute you discard for its cost. 
 
The rest of the deck is composed of STAPLES like the TTThrust package and consistency boosters like Foolish Burial and One for One. 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
Horus Bystial is a fairly simple deck to pilot since it doesn't have a singular straightforward combo. Summon as many monsters you can to field, gather as much resources as possible, control your opponent and then OTK on turn 3! 
 
This deck's many handtraps should slow your opponent's gameplan to a standstill, leaving your opponent's simplified board vulnerable to beatdown. 
 
Depending on what is in your hand and what you mill, you'll end on Bystial cards on hand and field + Synchro boss monsters, Hieratic Seals and if you have extenders, S:P Little Knight. 
 
If you have access to the Horus engine, you activate King's Sarcophagus -> Send 2 Horus monsters to GY by sending 2 cards -> XYZ summon Zombie Vampire -> Mill 4 + summon 1. That combo generally gets your plays started. 
 
Black Metal is the main normal summon of the deck, representing a Hieratic Seals (Normal Black Metal -> link away for Striker Dragon -> Search Red-Eyes Darkness -> Red-Eyes Darkness summons itself by banishing Striker Dragon -> Red-Eyes Darkness summons Black Metal from GY -> Link away both Dragons for Hieratic Seals). 
 
Going second, if you have Crimson Gaia in the backrow, it's ideal to go for the Crimson Dragon line to clear the board and OTK. Level 6 Bystial + Vision Resonator for Scarred Dragon Archfiend -> Bystial Dis Pater ensures that you destroy all your opponent's ATK position monsters during main phase, leaving their DEF position monsters to get destroyed by Red Dragon Archfiend's battle phase effect!
 
On the attack, Horus monsters are incredibly powerful beatsticks and King's Sarcophagus' non-targeting, non-destroying "send" outs most monsters. If your opponent removes any cards from your field when Horus monsters are fielded, you can punish them since all Horus monster's trigger effects occur with effects ranging from GY/banished recovery to sending a card on the field!
 
GENERAL TIPS
  • Chaos Angel made with Bystial Lubellion (Light) and Vision Resonator (Dark) is very hard to out for most opponents since it inherits both of its attribute dependant effects! With both light and dark, Chaos Angel is a nigh unstoppable juggernaut on the field.
  • If you get Droll'd, you can still make plays with the Horus engine since they don't search by adding to hand. It sends to GY, then summons from GY! This immediately makes this deck better dealing with Droll than its dragonic sibling Dragon Link, since this deck can keep playing despite the lingering floodgate.
  • If you get Shifter'd, try to end on defense position Chaos Angel. Sometimes, your opponent simply can't deal with an unaffected unkillable monster, giving you time to outlast Shifter's two turn lingering banish effect. 
  • If you're trading one interruption with 1 of your opponent's cards, you're usually ahead in resources. 
  • The effect you mostly want to resolve is Zombie Vampire's mill 4 and summon 1 from GY. Try to exhaust all your opponent's interactions before you attempt this crucial play. 
  • When siding out in games 2/3, the best cards to take out are 1 Chaos Space, 1 Levianeer, and 1 Branded Beast. If need be, the pilot can also side out the entire TTThrust package.
  • Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
Kailyn "Cookie" Cooksey-Garcia was definitely "COOKING" (sorry for the lame pun) when coming up with this topping YCS list! Bystials were a good meta call in a format dominated by meta decks that load the GY with lights/darks such as Unchained, Purrely and Tearlaments. Combining 3 advantage engines together (Horus, Bystial and Dragonlink) while handtrapping/controlling strategies to a standstill means that most games would lead to the duelist out-resourcing the opponent! 
 
This mid-range, staple oriented playstyle is certainly fun to play! It reminds me of playing PUNK or Live Twin, but this time with eldritch dragons and Egyptian themed guardians!
 
GLHF Duelists!

This is obviously a joke, but probably close to the kind of deck that Joey played at the beginning of the series. Just random monster cards that looked cool and/or had high attack/defense. The joke here is that he has Flame Swordsman, but no way to actually summon him.
Some cute cats with spoky ghosts (Purrely Ghostrick)

This is my version of a more realistic Solomon Muto's deck, the one that Yugi used against Kaiba in Ep.1, would have looked like. Considering that he was an expert in dueling, his deck would have been more competetive. I'm also assuming that at the time the show started, only cards pre-2004 were released so I only used cards from 2004 and before.

 

Credit for the original GOAT Format deck that was used as inspiration for this deck goes to the Common Collector. I had to swap out A Feather of the Phoenix, which was released in 2005. I decided to used Monster Reincarnation because it's effect basically does what Feather does, but not a great. I also removed the Toon cards because I'm assuming that Pegasus kept the Toon cards for himself. I went with Gather Your Mind, which isn't as great as Toon Table of Contents, but it'll do the job. I also added a 2nd Swords of Revealing Light in exchange for the Toon World.
Hbd anduween x2

This is what a more competetive version of Kaiba's deck might have looked like in Season 1, Ep. 1. Again I only used cards that had been release by 2004. Back when Yugi and Kaiba dueled for the first time, I would assume that the banlist would be the same one used for the Yugi-Kaiba Format, so I will go based on that banlist. (I.E. limited Monster Reborn, Pot of Greed, Change of Heart, Dark Hole and Raigeki.) The main reason I am going based on that banlist and not GOAT Format is because in Duelist Kingdom, Bakura used Change of Heart and so it had not been banned yet.

 

The inspiration for this deck came from Card Master Brian. The video is linked below.

Fire Kings with just the support from the Structure Deck.

send Garura, add Maximus => Special Maximus by banishing Garura => use Maximus effect to send Shuraig + Wind Pegasus => Shuraig effect add PoIix

deck_excerpt: It's just Pendulum at the end of the day
deck_description:
Out of the 3 Decks that premiered in the dumpster fire that was Ancient Guardians, I certainly like Solfachord the best. You will never catch me playing the floodgate brickfest that is Ursarctic and while Ogdoadic is really cool, Reptiles just do not have any good generic enablers or realistically anything much to end on other than Odgoabyss. And to be really fair, Solfachord really doesn't do much on its own because about half of their monsters are bad and most of their Spell/Traps functionally are too specific. TiSolfachord Beautia makes a card banished instead of going to the GY when it leaves the field and is also a battle trick. FaSolfachord Fancia gives battle protection for a Solfachord by destroying itself and adds a Solfachord from Deck to Extra Deck face-up. MiSolfachord Eliteia prevents battle damage and bounces a Spell/Trap on Summon. Solfachord Scale, Solfachord Symphony, Solfachord Harmonia, Solfachord Musica, and Solfachord Formal are all either very specific or they just don't do much at all. And while you could make an argument for Solfachord Musica, Exceed the Pendulum now exists which makes it a lot worse. But that leads to you needing to play a lot of the more generic Pendulum support and enablers which results in Solfachord becoming almost your average Pendulum combo Deck you would usually see or think of when you think of a Pendulum Deck. This Deck plays the Supreme King engine in order to facilitate Extra Deck plays and a low scale in addition to all of your Solfachord cards. 

Starting with the Solfachord monsters, the scale effects of your Solfacord monsters do not really matter all that much. There have 2 distinct effects. The Level 5 and higher Solfachords prevent your opponent from activating Spell/Trap Cards or monster effects when you Pendulum Summon a Solfachord monster while the Level 4 and lower Solfachords prevent the negation of the Pendulum Summons of your Solfachord monsters. Not the greatest scale effects, and they aren't exactly the most useful either considering that playing pure Solfachord as a Deck is pretty bad. We are playing 2 DoSolfachord Coolia, 1 LaSolfachord Angelia, 3 ReSolfachord Dreamia, and 3 DoSolfachord Cutia. Coolia can be Special Summoned from hand by Tributing 2 Pendulum Monsters which is almost never going to be the case due to Angelia. She can also target a face-up card your opponent controls and negate its effects until the end of your opponent's turn, but you can target 2 cards instead if you have an odd Pendulum Scale in your Pendulum Zone. I mean, yes, this is a good effect, but it is not a Quick Effect, so you can't use it on your opponent's turn and only are able to interact with your opponent on their turn with Coolia's next effect. When the effect of a monster on field is activated with an equal or lower ATK than the highest Pend Scale in your Pendulum Zone x300, you can Quick Effect destroy that monster. There are so many restrictions to this effect and all it does is destroy a monster. "Activated monster effect ON FIELD, with an EQUAL OR LOWER ATK then the HIGHEST PEND SCALE in your Pend Zone TIMES 300." The highest Pend Scale in this Deck is 8 which means that you can only pop a monster with 2400 or less ATK. If Supreme King Gate Infinity wasn't literally a walking detriment to you, then, this wouldn't be too much of a problem. The effect is still okay, but you are still pretty limited by what you are allowed to do. Angelia gives all of your Solfachord Pendulum Monsters an Armades effect for Spell/Traps while there is an odd Pend Scale in your Pend Zone which really is not anything worthwhile since we are only using her for her second effect. She can Tribute a Solfachord Pendulum Monster you control to Special Summon a Solfachord Pendulum Monster from your Deck whose Pend scale is 2 higher or 2 lower than the Tributed monster's. Angelia can tribute herself in order to get Coolia from the Deck which is the best and only worthwhile option. Dreamia can destroy itself to replace the destruction of your 1 Solfachord Pendulum Monster Cards by your opponent's card effect whiel you have an odd scale in your Pend Zone. I know that we are never gonna be using this effect for the most part, but I just want to comment on how bad this effect is. It does not replace the destruction of all of those cards. It ONLY replaces the destruction of ONE of those cards which is mindboggling. Either way, you can Special Summon her from hand if you control a Solfachord card in your Pend Zone. This gives good extension options to Link into something like Beyond the Pendulum, Exceed the Pendulum, Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess, or I:P Masquerena. Cutea gives all of your Solfachord Pend Monsters ATK equal to their respective Pend Scales x100 if you have an even scale in your Pend Zone. We aren't playing enough Solfachords to really make the best out of this effect. However, Cutea can search a Solfachord Pend Monster from Deck on Normal or Special Summon, and considering that she is a Level 1 Fairy monster, she can be Summoned off of Diviner of the Herald which is really nice for greater access. Moving onto the Supreme King Package. 1 Supreme King Gate Zero as a low scale and as a Supreme King Gate monster that can be accessed off of Gate Magician. Speaking of, 3 Supreme King Gate Magician. Its Pend Effect allows you to destroy it to place a Supreme King Gate Pend Monster from hand or Deck into your Pend Zone except for itself. This puts Gate Magician into your face-up Extra to Pend Summon it out later while also giving you a low scale. It's monster effect allows you to send a Pendulum Dragon, Xyz Dragon, Synchro Dragon, or Fusion Dragon monster from hand or Extra Deck to GY while you have a Supreme King Gate monster in your Pend Zone to Special Summon it from hand. And if its Normal or Special Summoned, it can search a card that mentions Z-ARC from Deck except for a Spellcaster monster. This makes it a great extender and play-enabler. 2 Supreme King Dragon Darkwurm and 1 Supreme King Dragon Lightwurm. I'm playing 2 Darkwurm because I really don't want to be drawing it, especially when Cutea or Diviner is a much better Normal Summon. If it's in GY while you control no monsters, you can Special Summon it, and if its Normal or Special Summoned, you can add a Supreme King Gate Pend Monster from Deck to hand. Lightwurm is both a high scale in a scale 8 and a Level 4 Tuner. This is important for making Borreload Savage Dragon or for situations where you need a high scale. If it's Normal or Special Summoned you can add a Supreme King Dragon or Suprem King Gate Pend Monster from Extra Deck to hand which may come up in cases where you need to put resources back into your hand. 3 Diviner of the Herald and 1 Trias Hierarchia. Diviner sends Hierarchia from Deck to GY on Normal or Special Summon, and while Hierarchia is in GY, it can Tribute Diviner to Summon itself back, and when Diviner is Tributed, you can Special Summon a Level 2 or lower Fairy monster from Deck except itself. This gets you Cutea for a search for a Solfachord monster and since you have both Cutea and Hierachia on field, that is automatically access to Beyond the Pendulum which is really good. And finally, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring and 3 Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit for handtraps. 

For Spell/Traps: 3 Pot of Prosperity. This isn't necessary at all, but it is very nice to see Diviner for easy access to Beyond the Pendulum through 1 card. You can definitely replace them with Tactics and Thrust if you want. 1 Foolish Burial and 3 Dragon Shrine for ways to send Darkwurm from Deck to GY. 2 Wings of Light which allows you to add a Supreme King Dragon or Supreme King Gate Pend Monster from Deck to hand. 3 Solfachord Elegance which allows you to choose 1 of 3 effects. You can Place a Solfachord Pendulum Monster from Deck into your Pendulum Zone, Add a Solfachord Pendulum Monster from hand to Extra Deck to scale 2 Solfachord Pendulum Monsters with 1 odd scale and 1 even scale from Deck, or you can add 1 odd and 1 even Pendulum Scale Monster from your Pend Zones to the Extra Deck to draw 2. You are usually going to be choosing from 1 of the first two effects, the first effect more often than not. And finally, 1 Called by the Grave and 1 Crossout Designator. 

Extra Deck: 1 Brave-Eyes Pendulum Dragon which is just a Pendulum Dragon name to send off of Gate Magician. It is possible to actually Summon our other name, Odd-Eyes Rebellion Xyz Dragon, so having an extra name to send helps, especially, since the Extra Deck is not very tight. 1 Odd-Eyes Vortex Dragon which bounces a face-up Attack Position monster your opponent controls on Special Summon and it can negate a Spell/Trap Card or monster effect by shuffling a face-up Pend Monster in your Extra Deck into the Deck, destroying that card. 1 Elder Entity N'tss. I really did not know what else could be put into the Extra Deck, so I just put N'tss in since it can be sent off of Herald for a pop. 1 Borreload Savage Dragon which can equip a Link from GY on Synchro Summon, giving it Borrel Counters equal to that monster's Link Rating, and you can remove 1 of them to negate a card or effect once per turn. 1 Odd-Eyes Absolute Dragon which is a Rank 7 that can easily be made by using 2 Gate Magicians and if its Xyz Summoned and sent to GY, you can Special Summon an Odd-Eyes monster from Extra Deck, usually being Vortex Dragon. 1 Odd-Eyes Rebellion Xyz Dragon which can detach a material to target up to 2 monsters your opponent controls with 3000 or less ATK and destroy them. If it is destroyed, you can put it in your Pend Zone and while it's in your Pend Zone, you can Special Summon it and then you can attach a DARK monster from GY to it as material. 1 Underworld Goddess of the Closed World which can use a monster your opponent controls as Link Material, and when its Link Summoned, you can negate the effects of all face-up monsters your opponent controls and it is unaffected by activated effects that don't target it. Once per turn, if your opponent activates a card or effect that would Special Summoning a monster(s) from the Gy, you can negate the activation. 1 Accesscode Talker, 1 Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess. 1 Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians who places Spell Counters on herself equal to the number of Spells on field and in GY on Link Summon and you can Quick Effect remove 3 Spell Counters to Special Summon a Spellcaster monster from hand or GY in Defense to a zone it points to. This is good for a quick Apollousa in your combo or easy access to Accesscode. 1 Beyond the Pendulum which adds a face-up Pend Monster from Extra Deck to hand on Link Summon and during the Main Phase, she can Quick Effect Special Summon a Pend Mosnter from hand or GY whose Level is between your scales in Defense. 1 S:P Little Knight and 1 I:P Masquerena. 2 Beyond the Pendulum which adds a Pend from Deck to hand on Link Summon by paying 1200 Life Points, but restricts you from activating monster effects and Pend Effects until your Pend Summon, and when you do Pend Summon two monsters with different original names to the zones it points to, you can target and destroy 2 cards on field. 

Side Deck: 3 Gameciel, the Sea Turtle Kaiju. 3 Droll & Lock Bird. 1 Crossout Designator. 1 Triple Tactics Talent. 2 Triple Tactics Thrust. 2 Dark Ruler No More. 3 Evenly Matched.

This is what I feel like Joey's deck would be like during Duelist Kingdom. With the help of Yugi, it's be slightly more competetive than his last deck, but it would still look like something off of Yugi-Kaiba Format. I decided the stick with Baby Dragon and Flame Swordsman because they held significance to him. The Baby Dragon because Yugi gave him Time Wizard and who better the pair the Time Wizard up with? Baby Dragon! Flame Swordsman is obvious because that's Joey's favorite card.
Winged Dragon of Ra
Obelisk deck

This is what Mai's deck might have looked like coming into Duelist Kingdom. It's more consistent that the deck she used in the anime. The reason I did not used Cyber Harpie Lady is because I'm staying true to only cards released in 2004 and before. Plus, using the original Harpie Lady gives the deck a je ne sais quoi kind of feel. 

 

The inspiration for this deck came from The Retro Expert! I love this guy's GOAT decks! Go check him out if you want to build a fun GOAT deck.

Again, I feel like Yugi, being the type of duelist that he is, would have multiple decks for Duelist Kingdom. His Grandfather's card shop would allow for this and so each battle will feature a new deck. This deck would suit him for his battle against Mako, since Gaia the Dragon Champion was the monster he used to defeat Mako and this deck is a more consistent version of the deck.

 

The inspiration for this deck goes to The Retro Expert's GOAT Format Gaia the Dragon Champion deck. His video is linked.

This is my take on what a competetive version of Mako's deck would look like. IK he didn't reveal having The Legendary Fisherman until Battle City. But I thought it would be better to introduce it now, because he does mention about his dad during this episode and a person like Mako would use this card in his deck. This would also be a fun way of taking control over the game, since Duelist Kingdom has a rule that duelists cannot attack directly and The Legendary Fisherman with A Legendary Ocean would be one more obstacle that Yugi would have to overcome during his duel with Mako.

 

Credit for the inspiration for this deck goes to, once again, The Retro Expert. His video is linked.

This deck is pretty much the same as his last deck, but instead he's added the Lava Battleguard to pair up with his Swamp Battleguard. Although he did not run the Swamp Battleguard in his last deck, I did add it to his original S1E1 deck, which means he had that card already.

So I decided that Rex Raptor will not play Red-Eyes Black Dragon in this deck, however it will still be a rare card that he's come across and bet to Joey if Joey beats him. The boss monster that Joey will defeat is Black Tyranno. Now this is a 2nd place dinosaur deck, at least of their time. The one he runs in the anime would have lost round 1. It will still lose to Joey's Time Wizard, but at least this deck is more of what a 2nd place world champion would play.

 

The inspiration for this deck, once again, comes from The Retro Expert. Video is linked.

This is my version of Panic's deck that he used against Mai and Yugi in Season 1 Episode 14. Although he still ends up losing to Yugi's Gaia the Dragon Warriro deck, this deck is more viable than the one he plays in the anime.

 

Inspiration for this deck came from Oscar JOEY V10. The video is linked.
