deck_description:
Gizmek is a very interesting archetype that consists of Machine monsters from Levels 1 to 10 whose ATK and DEF equal each other and have effects related to Machine monsters and/or monsters with equal ATK and DEF in general as well as banished card and/or face-down banished cards. I remember testing out Gizmek Ancient Gear when the extended Gizmek support came out in Dawn of Majesty before I realized that Ancient Gear is still really bad. Either way, our Level 9 that we are taking a look at today for Prediction Princess is Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag, but this Deck focuses on both it and Gizmek Makami, the Ferocious Fanged Fortress. Kaku can actually be placed into many different versions of Prediction Princess, with it even being capable of being utilized as a going second removal option, but it is still a very easy-to-summon Level 9 monster whose Type and Attribute are good as a target on field for World Legacy Monstrosity. Makami, on the other hand, can search any monster whose ATK equals its own DEF. This includes Prediction Princess Bibliomuse who has 2500 ATK and 2500 DEF. This Deck aims on utilizing Kaku, Makami, and our 3rd Gizmek that I have yet to mention, Gizmek Inaba, the Hopping Hare of Hakuto, alongside several Small World bridges to get to our Prediction Princess plays. Is this a good version of Prediction Princess? Not really. It is one of those acceptable versions of Prediction Princess that work, but it still doesn't compare to Runick Prediction Princess and pure Ham Prediction Princess which I believe are the best versions of Prediction Princess.

For the monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei and 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith. I decided to play this ratio of the Rituals because we are playing Pre-Preparation of Rites alongside Prediction Ritual to make up for the 1 fatal flaw of Gizmek Makami which is that Makami is a Level 6. Yes, Makami can be Normal Summoned without Tributing which I will get to later, but without a Pre-Prep package, this Deck would be a lot more inconsistent. Pre-Prep allows you to search for Tarotrei and Prediction Ritual while Makami gets you Bibliomuse without the usage of World Legacy Monstrosity. While we have a couple of Monstrosity lines, it is still safer to have multiple ways of accessing Bibliomuse in this Deck which is through Makami, Monstrosity, and Small World (and Pot of Prosp if that counts). Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during the End Phase. Tarotreith can be Special Summoned by Tarotrei's End Phase effect and she can Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down and on Flip, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from Deck face-down. 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse which can Summon herself back face-down if she was Tributed and sent to GY, and on Flip, she can add a Prediction Princess monster except herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand. Also, while she is face-up on field, she gives all of your Ritual Monsters targeting and destruction protection from your opponent's card effects. 2 Deus-X Krawler which negates the activated effects of your opponent's monsters on field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed while on field, it can add a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute than it from Deck to hand. For the Gizmeks: 3 Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag, 3 Gizmek Makami, the Ferocious Fanged Fortress, and 2 Gizmek Inaba, the Hopping Hare of Hakuto. Kaku can be Special Summoned from hand if there is a monster in the Extra Monster Zone. While on field, it can target a face-up monster in the Extra Monster Zone and equip it to itself. And when it destroys a monster by battle, you can Special Summon the equipped monster. Kaku is a very easy-to-summon Level 9, especially when we can just Link off Inaba or Diviner for Salamangreat Almiraj or use Instant Fusion to Summon Master of Ham into your EMZ. And it is also a pretty unique form of removal for going second. Makami can be Normal Summoned without Tribute if you have 6 or more banished cards which means that Pot of Prosperity is functionally a combo piece funnily enough because you banish 6 cards from your Extra Deck to search. On Normal or Special Summon, Makami can discard a monster to add a monster whose ATK equals its own DEF from Deck to hand and when its destroyed in the Monster Zone, you can shuffle 6 of your banished cards into the Deck. As I said before, Makami can search Bibliomuse, but it can also search for Kaku if you already have Bibliomuse which is nice for Link plays, Rank 9 plays, or extending with a Monstrosity. And yes, Bibliomuse will trigger if it is tributed for a Tribute Summon, but it is a bit of a waste if you do so because you really want Bibliomuse to be used for Ritual fodder for herself to be brought back, flipped to search, and potentially be used as Ritual fodder again. Inaba Special Summons a Machine monster whose ATK equals its own DEF from hand in DEF on Normal Summon. Its other effect is basically irrelevant in this Deck because we aren't playing enough Machines whose ATK and DEF are equal. Inaba basically plays around you having to Normal Summon Makami. We are only playing 2 of it because we aren't playing that many Machine monsters whose ATK equals their DEF, so drawing multiple copies most likely will result in a dead hand. But since it is a good Small World bridge, it is still worth playing. 3 Diviner of the Herald who sends a Fairy from Deck or Extra Deck to GY on Normal or Special Summon, increasing its own Level by the Level of the sent monster. If you take a look at the Extra Deck, you can see that we are playing Trickstar Band Sweet Guitar which is a Level 7 Fairy Monster. Because we are playing Kaku who is a Level 9 FIRE Machine monster, you can send Sweet Guitar or any Level 7 Fairy, I recommend from the Extra Deck, with Diviner in order to make her a Level 9 as a Monstrosity target on field. This is good if you already have Bibliomuse access but don't have any Ritual access as you can Summon Kaku and Deus-X from Deck with Monstrosity and go through the Aggregator line to get what you need. And finally, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring. 

Spell/Traps: 1 Instant Fusion for Master of Ham. 3 Pot of Prosperity. 3 Small World which actually is incredible in this Deck or any Gizmek-focused Deck. Because if you didn't know, all of the Gizmek monsters have different Levels, different stats, and different Attributes with the only thing that they share in common being their Machine-typing. If you manage to bridge from a monster in hand to any Gizmek monster in Deck, you can search any Gizmek monster from your Deck or any monster with an associated Attribute as the rest of their stats, Types, and Attributes work. And while I would really like to have a Gizmek that would allow me to bridge from any Gizmek to any other Gizmek to Diviner, Gizmek Naganaki, the Sunrise Signaler is a Level 2 which means that it can't bridge to Herald, so your only option would be to bridge from Kaku to Bibliomuse to Diviner. 2 Pre-Preparation of Rites. 2 Prediction Ritual. It is important to remember that this card can ONLY Ritual Summon Tarotrei and not Tarotreith. You can also banish it from GY except the turn it was sent there to search a Prediction Princess monster. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which Ritual Summons a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or Gy face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess from Deck face-down. And finally, 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon a Level 9 monster from hand or target a Level 9 monster on field and Special Summon 2 Level 9 Monsters with different Types and Attributes thatn the targeted monster from Deck, but they are destroyed during the End Phase. 

Extra Deck: 1 Trickstar Band Sweet Guitar. 1 Master of Ham who Special Summons a Flip Monster from Deck face-down on Fusion Summon. 2 Herald of the Arc Light for a Ritual search when sent to GY. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 1 Infinitrack Earth Slicer which can detach any number of materials to destroy an equal number of cards on field, and it can attach a monster it destroys by battle to it as material, making it a great Zeus enabler in addition to board clearing. 2 Mereologic Aggregator which sends a monster from Extra Deck to Gy on Xyz Summon, which is usually Herald for a Ritual search, and it can detach any number of materials and attach the same number of monsters from GY which recycles Herald for another search when Aggregator leaves the field. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Nine-Lives Cat. 1 S:P Little Knight. 1 I:P Masquerena. 1 Salamangreat Almiraj. 1 Gravity Controller. 

Side Deck: 2 Nibiru, the Primal Being. 3 Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju. 3 Triple Tactics Thrust. 1 Triple Tactics Talent. 2 Dark Ruler No More. 1 Change of Heart. And 3 Evenly Matched.

deck_excerpt: FIGHT FIRE WITH FIRE WITH RESCUE-ACE! Featuring the newest member, Promethean Fire Princess!
deck_description:
Rescue-ACE is arguably the strongest deck build pack deck from the set "Amazing Defenders." So naturally, when they came to Masterduel, I immediately took interest in them as a competitive deck to climb ladder with! Although they are not full power yet, they are a force to be reckoned with on ladder with their immense resource advantage generation as well as ability to confidently play first or second! 

The surprise debut and release of Promethean Princess in pack "Record of Noble Spirits" give Rescue-ACE an additional win condition - a recur-able boss monster that generates resources, provides interruption, and summons itself from the GY extremely easily! 
 
If you want to reach high levels on Masterduel ladder with a reliable deck that can either 1st or 2nd and can cram a ton of staples while being consistently powerful, Rescue-ACE is a good deck to invest in! 
 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
The deck is currently best played "pure." The standard RESCUE-ACE core is included, numbering 22 cards. 5 Rescue-ACE spells/traps are included as targets for Turbulence to set from deck. REINFORCE! isn't included since the card seems fairly inconsequential compared to the other quick-play spells and traps. One for One is included since it's an additional copy of Hydrant which can be summoned from deck. 
 
A whopping 19 STAPLES is included in the deck. The usual "Maxx C" package is included so the pilot can win the Maxx C minigame. A package of "Triple Tactics Thrust" is included to help the duelist deal with threats like Purrely Noir (Herald of the Abyss) or to search a starter from deck (One for One). 
 
The Extra Deck isn't used much except for Sunlight Wolf, Promethean Princess and Amblowhale. Other than that, there are a toolbox of Extra Deck answers to specific game states. Most of the time, the Extra Deck monsters are banish targets for Pot of Prosperity. 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
Rescue-ACE functions as a control-centred midrange deck. Usually, the deck summons Turbulence, sets 4 spells/traps from the deck (two interruptions and two follow-up cards). If there are additional extenders, boards also will end on Promethean Princess in the GY with Amblowhale for an additional two interruptions. The hand also may have Rescue-ACE warriors that function as handtraps to net further advantage from deck, hand or GY. 
 
Currently, this deck only functions as a "one trick pony" - doing the same basic predictable strategy everygame as stated above. Here is the deck's main combo: 
 
Rescue-ACE Hydrant + Rescue-ACE Extender = 4 set Rescue-ACE spells/traps (interruption and follow-up) + Promethean Princess in GY (monster destruction) + Amblowhale (link-monster summon and 1 card destruction)
  1. Normal summon Hydrant. Special summon Extender (Extenders could be Fire Engine, Fire Attacker, or a monster summoned via Rescue-AC warrior during your opponent's turn). 
  2. Activate Hydrant's effect to search Turbulence from deck. 
  3. Link away Hydrant + Extender for Salamangreat Sunlight Wolf. 
  4. Summon Turbulence from hand by banishing 2 Rescue-ACE cards in the your GY to the zone Sunlight Wolf points to. 
  5. Activate Sunlight Wolf's effect to recover a fire monster from the GY (you can recover Ash Blossom for example!)
  6. Activate Turbulence's effect to set 4 Rescue-ACE spells/traps from deck. Typically, you'd set ALERT! (search), RESCUE! (monster reborn), EXTINGUISH! (destroy monster) and CONTAIN! (monster negate). 
  7. Link away Sunlight Wolf + Turbulence to summon Promethean Princess. 
  8. Promethean Princess summons any Fire monster from GY. If applicable, summon Hydrant, then you can get an additional search with ALERT!
  9. Link away Promethean Princess + Fire monster for Amblowhale.
  10. During your opponent's turn, summon a Rescue-ACE monster from your GY to turn on your Rescue-ACE traps.  
It may not seem like much, but this much interruption coupled with the resource advantage that Rescue-ACE inherently generates is usually enough to win games! Often times after you interrupt an opponent enough they stop on a weak board, leaving you to OTK the next turn!
 
Going second, the sheer amount of staples that this deck pilots try to slow/stop your opponent completely. Boards are also broken by the Triple Tactics Thrust package. Also, the Rescue-ACE warrior monsters summon from deck, hand and GY whenever your opponent activates a monster effect on the field. 
 
GENERAL TIPS
  • This deck doesn't have EMERGENCY! yet, thus decreasing this strategy's consistency. Piri Reis map is an option to search for Hydrant, which gets plays started.  
  • Promethean Fire Princess may lock you into fire, but that's only when it's on the field! When you link her away for Amblowhale or another fire card, that's when you're free summon other monster attributes. 
  • Hydrant can be linked away into Relinquished Anima! Opponents surprisingly leave many monsters vulnerable in the zones in front of the Extra Monster Zones, so when you have used Hydrant's effect to search, you may as well use it as a boardbreaker!
  • In a pinch, Bagooska can be made easily in this deck by summoning two of your level 4 warrior monsters!
  • Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
If you think Rescue-ACE is strong right now, just wait until EMERGENCY! and Preventer are out in Masterduel! These two elevate the strategy to the next level of competitive power! Until then, Rescue-ACE is still a midrange powerhouse for its resource generation and simple but powerful gameplan. With Rescue-ACE, you're sure to "rescue" your ailing Masterduel ladder record! (sorry for the bad pun lol)
 
GLHF Duelists!
This is the Elemental Hero Deck that Jaden Yuki used in Yu-Gi-Oh! GX anime through all of Season 1 and the first part of Season 2.

deck_excerpt: Enjoyable to play with a competitive edge.
deck_description:
Always go first. The less disruption to face down, the better.

Play 'Allure of Darkness' to strengthen your current hand, but, be careful not to suicide your whole hand. Play 'Piercing the Darkness' as soon as you get it.

There are two strategies to pursue, depending on the cards you have. The first strategic aim is to access 'Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon' though 'Red-Eyes Fusion'. All other times, the strategic priority is to Summon/Special Summon as many monsters to the field as possible, in order to access XYZ and Link monsters in the Extra Deck.

Use 'Red-Eyes Insight' to search 'Red-Eyes Fusion'. Another way of searching 'Red-Eyes Fusion' is to activate the Graveyard Effect of 'Red-Eyes Black Meteor Dragon', however, you cannot activate this effect on the same turn it was sent to the Graveyard, so this play requires some setup. For a secondary target for 'Red-Eyes Insight' search 'Return of the Red-Eyes' which helps flood the field with monsters. 'Return of the Red-Eyes' synergises extremely well with 'Piercing the Darkness' enabling the player to draw a card when they Summon a Normal Monster once per turn. For example: On your turn 'Return of the Red-Eyes' activates and Summons a Normal Monster from the Graveyard to the field, which triggers 'Piercing the Darkness' allowing you to draw a card. At the start of the opponent's turn, the process repeats.

If going for the Fusion Summon, a major weakness to beware is that 'Ash Blossom' can negate 'Red-Eyes Fusion' with a deadly lingering-effect. Since the effect of 'Red-Eyes Fusion' would be negated, and not the activation, the summoning restriction effect of 'Red-Eyes Fusion' still resolves, thus the player cannot summon anything else that turn. You can counter 'Ash Blossom' with 'Called by the Grave' should you be fortunate enough to have it in hand.

A second method of Fusion Summoning 'Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon' can be accessed through 'Magicalised Fusion' and is very easy to satisfy if 'Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon' has already been brought out once already using 'Red-Eyes Fusion'.

'Red-Eyes Soul' is an excellent hand trap that allows you to Special Summon 'Red-Eyes Darkness Metal' from the deck to the field. Its condition is easy to satisfy, only requiring your opponent Special Summon a monster. Summoning 'Red-Eyes Darkness Metal' using this method is a priority.'Red-Eyes Darkness Metal' helps to flood the field during your main phase by Special Summoning one Dragon monster from the hand or Graveyard. 'Noctovision Dragon' chains nicely to the resolution of 'Red-Eyes Soul'.

For going second, 'Evenly Matched' is very useful. 'Bystial Magnahamut' is excellent going second, use it on the opponent's turn to add 'The Black Stone of Legend' to hand at the end of their turn.

For some back row destruction 'Dark Armed, The Dragon of Annihilation' can target and destroy front or back row, for the cost of banishing a card in your Graveyard. The effect can be used twice in one turn. 'Harpies Feather Duster' also helps. Consider cards in the Side Deck when facing spell and trap heavy decks.

Red-Eyes Black Dragon is a metaphor about the power of potential. This deck is enjoyable to play and has a competitive edge. I would gauge its power at around Tier 2 or 3.

Since debuting at locals on [2023-10-17], this deck has bested:

[Kashtira]
[Eldlich]
[Swordsoul]
[Blue-Eyes]

deck_excerpt: The original Prediction Princess build revitalized
deck_description:
When Prediction Princess Tarotrei and the rest of the original cast of Prediction Princesses debuted in Dragons of Legend 2 back in 2015, Shaddolls were realistically the only Flip Monsters you could conceivably play with them aside from Guard Dog, Whirlwhind Weasel, and Pot of the Forbidden. This is because Shaddolls were the only Flip Archetype at the time which meant that the Flip Monsters you were playing had synergy with each other and they were not just random Flip Monsters that you tossed into the Deck just because they were good. Even so, Pre-Preparation of Rites still wouldn't be released until 2016 which meant that you were basically playing Shaddoll until you could find Tarotrei and Ritual Summon her, and from there, you would have to do your best on trying to keep Tarotrei on the field or find more ways to access more copies if she were to be removed from the field. Yes, it was a really cool Deck, but it gave a feeling of playing Shaddoll with Tarotrei on the side. Even after we got cards like Pre-Preparation of Rites and Deus-X Krawler and all of the Shaddoll support from Structure Deck Shaddoll Showdown, there was really no truly good way to play Shaddoll with Prediction Princess. They synergized with each other but their individual pieces in the Deck didn't meld well together because Shaddoll was fully capable of functioning by itself while Prediction Princess and Tarotrei were clunky pieces that were hard to access. Shaddoll Schism fixed some of those issues as it made it so that you didn't need to play as many names to go into the real powerhouses of Shaddoll, being their Fusions, but at that time, there was already a much better Deck that facilitated it much better in Invoked Shaddoll Dogmatika. I wanted to play Shaddoll and Prediction Princess together in the same Deck, and in the same combo. And this Deck achieves that to a fairly decent degree and that is due to it inheriting both the flaws of Shaddoll and Prediction Princess in that you have no easy way to search Shaddoll Spell/Traps without much investment through getting El Shaddoll Apkallone into the GY or through Flipping Shaddoll Hedgehog and that there is no inherent way to search for Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. The Level 9 Monsters we are taking a look at here in this version of Prediction Princess is Helshaddoll Hollow and El Shaddoll Anoyatyllis, but mainly Anoyatyllis. You see, Anoyatyllis requires a Shaddoll monster and a WATER monster for its Fusion Materials. For one, I am not going to play Naelshaddoll Ariel for a WATER monster and you can bet me that I am not playing Prediction Princess Crystaldine for the same reason. Ghost Sister & Spooky Dogwood and King of the Swamp don't count either because they literally do nothing in this Deck. So, we are playing Nephe Shaddoll Fusion to create ourselves a WATER monster to Fuse. Yes, this is basically a 4 card combo, but this is the only way that I can conceivably play Shaddolls and Prediction Princess in the same Deck, go through their cards in my main combo, and end on a board that includes monsters from both sides. 

For the Main Deck monsters, we are starting off with the same song and dance: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotreith and 1 Prediction Princess Tarotrei. Tarotreith can be Ritual Summoned or Summoned from hand or GY via Tarotrei's End Phase effect. On Flip, it can Summon a Flip Monster from Deck face-down and as a Quick Effect, it can Flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Tarotrei can Quick Effect Flip a monster face-up or face-down and can Summon a Flip Monster from hand or Gy in face-down Defense Position during the End Phase. 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse which on Flip adds a Prediction Princess monster other than itself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand. If it's Tributed and sent to GY, it can Summon itself back face-down, and while on field, it gives your Ritual Monsters targeting and destruction protection. 2 Deus-X Krawler which negates all of your opponent's monsters' activated effects on field after it has been flipped face-up, and when it's destroyed on field, it can add a Level 9 with a different Type and Attribute than it from Deck to hand. For the Shaddoll monsters: 1 Helshaddoll Hollow, 3 Shaddoll Squamata, 3 Shaddoll Hedgehog, and 3 Reeshaddoll Wendi. For their Flip Effects: Hollow targets a face-up monster your opponent controls and sends a Shaddoll monster with the same Attribute from your Extra Deck to the GY to banish that monster. Squamata targets and destroys a monster on field. Hedgehog adds a Shaddoll Spell/Trap from Deck to hand. It is VERY important to remember not to activate Hedgehog's effect when it is sent to GY by an effect. Shaddoll monsters can only use 1 effect per turn and only once that turn which means you either get their GY effect or their Flip Effect. You see, if Wendi is sent to GY by an effect, she can Special Summon a Shaddoll from Deck face-down which you are going to be using to get Hedgehog. Later in your combo when you are using Tarotreith to flip your monsters face-up, you can flip multiple monsters which means that you can flip Hedgehog face-up in addition to Bibliomuse, giving you the ability to search for Shaddoll Schism to use as a part of your endboard. 99% of the time, you get nothing out of searching a Shaddoll off of Hedgehog's GY effect, so it is important to keep this in mind. Moving onto Wendi, her Flip Effect alllows you to Special Summon a Shaddoll monster from Deck in face-up or face-down Defense Position. For their GY effects: Hollow sends cards from the top of your Deck to the GY equal to the number of different Attributes of monsters on the field. Squamata sends a Shaddoll card from Deck to GY. As an alternate to the Hedgehog spiel from earlier, if you fuse with Squamata, you can send Schism from Deck to GY, and when you detach Anoyatyllis from Aggregator, Anoyatyllis can add back said Schism. Next, Hedgehog can add a Shaddoll monster from Deck to hand which you do not need to do 99% of the time, and Wendi Special Summons a Shaddoll from Deck face-down which is usually going to be Hedgehog.

For Spell/Traps: 1 Instant Fusion which can get either Master of Ham or El Shaddoll Winda. You see, if you draw Instant Fusion, Nephe Shaddoll Fusion, and another Shaddoll, you can actually Instant Fusion into Winda, equip Winda with Nephe Shaddoll Fusion and change its Attribute to WATER, and fuse into Anoyatyllis. This is because Winda counts Summons while it is on field as opposed to something like Summon Limit which can count Summons even before it is activated. So that is something cool to keep in mind. 1 Shaddoll Fusion because maybe you draw it going second and you can fuse 2 Shaddolls with different Attributes from Deck to make Apkallone to negate a face-up card and search a Shaddoll card when it's sent to GY. 3 Nephe Shaddoll Fusion which is an Equip Spell that equips to a Shaddoll monster, changing its Attribute to an Attribute of your choice, and while it's equipped, you can Fuse into a Shaddoll Fusion Monster using the equipped monster and a monster from hand or field. This gets you your WATER for Anoyatyllis most importantly. 1 Foolish Burial. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which which can either Special Summon a Level 9 monster from hand or target a Level 9 monster on field and Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters with different names with a different Type and Attribute than the targeted monster. 2 Emergency Teleport as 2 extra ways to access Wendi for another Shaddoll to fuse with. 3 Pot of Prosperity. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down. And you can banish it during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess from Deck face-down. 3 Infinite Impermanence. And 1 Shaddoll Schism which can Fusion Summon a Shaddoll Fusion Monster by banishing monsters from field or Gy, then, it allows you to send a monster your opponent controls with the same Attribute as the monster you Summoned to the Gy.

Extra Deck: 1 El Shaddoll Anoyatyllis which can be made with a Shaddoll and a WATER monster. It does prevent both players from Special Summoning monsters from the hand or GY using Spell/Trap effects, but this will never come up or be a detriment to you because it is just a Level 9 to make Aggregator at the end of the day. And if it's sent to GY, it can target and add a Shaddoll Spell/Trap from GY to hand. 1 El Shaddoll Construct which can be made with a Shaddoll and a LIGHT monster. On Special Summon, you can send a Shaddoll card from Deck to GY, and if it battles a Special Summoned monster, it destroys that monster at the start of the damage step. And it can target and add back a Shaddoll Spell/Trap from GY to hand when it's sent to GY. 1 El Shaddoll Apkallone which can be made with 2 Shaddoll monsters with different Attributes. On Special Summon, it can negate the effects of a face-up card on the field and if it is sent to GY, you can add any Shaddoll card from Deck or GY to hand and then discard 1 card. 1 El Shaddoll Winda which can be made with a Shaddoll and a DARK monster. It cannot be destroyed by your opponent's effects and it limits both plays to Special Summoning once per turn when it's face-up on field. And it recycles a Shaddoll Spell/Trap from GY when it's sent there. 1 Master of Ham which Special Summons a Flip Monster from Deck face-down on Fusion Summon or when its flipped face-up. And funnily enough, since we are playing a lot of Flip Monsters, you can banish 2 Flip monsters from GY or face-up field to Special Summon it from GY in face-down Defense Position. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which is a Ritual Search when sent to GY. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 1 Infinitrack Earth Slicer. 1 Mereologic Aggregator which can send a monster from Extra Deck to GY on Xyz Summon, and it can target monsters in your GY and detach an equal number of Xyz Materials to attach those monsters to itself which can be used to loop Herald. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 S:P Little Knight, 1 I:P Masquerena, and 1 Gravity Controller.

Side Deck: 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Ultimate Slayer, 3 Triple Tactics Thrust, 1 Triple Tactics Talent, 2 Dark Ruler No More, and 3 Evenly Matched.

deck_excerpt: Melffy Tri-Brigade / NA Remote Duel Extravaganza Top 8
deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Deck

Tournament Meta Decks are current level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. There are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Chris Bacon
Tournament: NA Remote Duel Extravaganza - October 10th 2021
Placement: Top 32

Symphonic Warriors are a mostly forgotten archetype that were first released in 2017 as a part of Raging Tempest. Originally, the archetype was unplayable as a standalone deck as they lacked the appriopriate cards to function by themselves. The most play they saw was being used an engine with Guitaar and Miccs. I personally used to run them in a Clownblade deck with the Star Seraphone engine back then.

In 2022, however; they received support cards in Dimension Force. These new cards completely changed the deck and allowed them to not only be playable as a standalone deck, but could actually make fairly decent end boards. Since then, although the archetype has continued to remain largely unknown or forgotten, Symphonic Warriors have only become stronger thanks to cards such as Barrone De Fleur and the Therion cards. 

But as fun and powerful as Symphonic Warriors can be, they suffer from two primary weaknesses. Firstly, they have very limited starting combos, heavily relying on opening Synthess along with DJJ. Because of that, cards such as Scrap Golem and Crystron Rosenix were added to allow Scrap Recycler to become a one card combo in cases of extremely unplayable hands. Of course, the end board will be nothing great but still better than nothing. Those two cards also do not negatively affect your hands that much, so drawing them isn't too much of a problem as they can be pendulum summoned or used as discard fodder for Guitaar.

The other weakness is consistency. Because they already suffer from a limited amount of starting combos, Symphonic Warriors practically live or die on being able to access them. Unfortunately, they do not have their own search card, hence why Small World and Ignknight Reload are needed.  Upstart Goblin can be replaced but still benefits consistency.

As for other details? The reason why the Therion cards are not played at maximum copies is because of the end boards Symphonic Warriors can create. They, alone, are able to create boards with 4-5 negates. Thus, the Therion cards are not always necessary but still add to the end boards nonetheless. And the reason for Planet Finder is because of opening hands with cards that would normally be searched during combos. So, it was chosen to be added as an additional target by Gear Gigant X, which then will be pendulum summoned and used to search the Therion field spell.

Symphonic Warriors are a fun but frustating deck to play. They can create strong boards, however; they suffer from many weaknesses such as consistency, linear combos, and struggling to go second. Although they aren't able to compete with the meta, they're still great for casual tournaments or for some simple, plain fun.
